<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-016-093 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 445 446</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Nov 5 1991 v5 n38 p5(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Apple plots course for its Unix operating system: QuickTime,easier installation highlight A/UX 3.0. (new version of Apple Unixoperating system)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ratcliffe, Mitch.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Apple outlines plans for future versions of its A/UX Unixoperating system for the Macintosh.andP;  A/UX 3.0 will reportedlyinclude the company's new QuickTime multimedia extensions and willbe easier to install than A/UX 2.0.andP;  it is also compatible withSystem 7.0 and the new Macintosh Quadra systems.andP;  Apple introducedA/UX 3.0 at its Unix Expo trade show and discussed plans for A/UX4.0, which will be based on the Open Software Foundation's OSF/1kernel.andP;  A/UX 4.0 will ship in late 1993 or early 1994 and willrun on either the Motorola 680x0 or Motorola/IBM Power PC RISCprocessor.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (Product development).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Product:   A/UX 3.0 (Operating system) (Product development).andO;Topic:     UNIXMultimedia SoftwareOperating SystemsProduct Development.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>QuickTime, easier installation highlight A/UX 3.0andM;By Mitch RatcliffeandM;New York -- Apple last week laid out the course its Unix operating systemwill take over the next four years.andM;The company briefed attendees at Unix Expo here on upgrades that will makeits A/UX system compatible first with System 7 and eventually with IBMCorp.'s AIX.andM;In describing its new Unix computing environment, PowerOpen, which was partof last month's Apple/IBM alliance announcement, Apple assured users thatA/UX will remain an integral part of its OS offerings.andM;&quot;During the '80s, IS folks saw a proliferation of incompatible systems,&quot; saidJim Groff, marketing manager for Apple's Enterprise Computing Division.andP;  &quot;Nowthe business has changed, and we don't believe these people are going to buyuntil they get compatible systems.&quot;andM;andgt;A/UX 4.0.andP;  The first Unix OS from Apple to be based on the Open SoftwareFoundation's OSF/1 kernel will ship in late 1993 or early 1994, according toApple's Unix Expo announcement.andP;  It will run on either the Motorola 680x0chip or the Motorola/IBM-designed PowerPC RISC (reduced instruction setcomputing) chip.andM;The new Apple Unix will share the OSF/1 kernel and a set of common tools andlibraries with IBM's AIX.andP;  However, A/UX will retain unique features thatwill Groff also said a set of libraries will deliver A/UX features on the newTaligent OS, due at mid-decade from Apple and IBM's new joint venture.andM;andgt;A/UX 3.0.andP;  As expected, Apple took the wraps off its System 7- andQuadra-compatible A/UX at the show (see MacWEEK, Oct.andP;  29).andM;New for A/UX is the familiar Apple Installer and the capability to selectindividual modules of Unix functionality for installation on users' harddisks.andP;  For example, an ordinary user can choose not to have the developmenttools in Unix installed, saving as much as 50 Mbytes of disk space.andM;Support for third-party hard drives also is included in the installer.andO;Previously, A/UX provided only Apple hard disk drive drivers.andM;A/UX 3.0 also will include QuickTime, the company's new multimediatechnology, which will support sound, video and animation in either the MacOS or Unix.andO;</TEXT></DOC>